End of ramble.

Whatever conditions are present, there's a lot of value in learning to manage your risk, especially when conditions aren't 'up only' and greed is rewarded.

Part of that risk management comes down to setting your trade parameters (levels of invalidation), sizing, targets, etc.

There's no cookie-cutter solution. It takes a lot of time to understand what you're best at and what the market gives you in real time.

Market conditions will change, and your setups will stop working as well as they did. Other times you'll be in sync with things and winning.

One of the more difficult things regarding trading is sitting on your hands and waiting for things to play out based on your setup.

Setting invalidation levels and criteria for your trades is essential and helps you deal with the uncertainty and noise from Twitter.

I held onto my $BONK airdrop when I first received it because the dollar amount received wouldn't change my life, therefore selling it at that time would give me little value and would put a ceiling on my potential upside.

Now it's up 200x and I'm a happy boy.

When I receive a free airdrop, I think of things this way:

If I sell now, will the money change my life in any way? If the answer is yes, I sell a good amount and capture its value.

If the answer is no, I hold onto it and forget about it. 

Either way I win.

4) You can try the route I took; create a twitter account and look to connect with smart people on the platform and figure your shit out as you go.

2) Ask yourself: What skills do you have that you can monetize?

8) If you track influencer/NFT trader wallets, you'll notice that they receive a lot of NFTs. 

The majority of the NFTs that are sent to them are from scammers trying to get you to mint. Always be cautious of this.

7) Take your time. The greatest mistakes are usually made when you're feeling pressured or rushed.

5) If it's too good to be true, it likely is.

6) You'll often receive random NFTs and shitcoins to your NFT wallet. If you don't recognize the airdrop, do not try and sell it. Do not send it elsewhere; simply don't touch it.

4) Many project's discord channels have been hacked in the past. The hackers will typically post in the channel saying there's a mint happening. 

You'll then rush to connect and mint, getting your wallet drained. Always be weary of mints than haven't previously been announced.

3) You'll inevitably receive DMs on twitter, discord and other social media platforms from people impersonating the team members/project. 

Never click on any URLs or engage with them. It's almost always a scam.

2) Always ensure you're on the proper URL/website/social media page when looking to mint your NFT.

There are many impersonators and fake accounts out there that want to steal your precious cryptocurrency.

That doesn't mean you shouldn't have any in your portfolio, $BTC is one of a kind and serves its purpose. However you're not going 100x your portfolio.

It's not a popular thing to talk about, but you have to be smart with whatever cards you're dealt. Even if you won a few hands, all it takes is a couple bad moves to get you back to where you started.

Even if you're a millionaire, your spending habits are likely to grow as you access higher tiers of objects and experiences to purchase. I know many millionaires who went broke because they didn't manage that well.
One way to "make it" is managing how much you spend on things in your life. It's perfectly fine to indulge and use your money to live the life you want, but you have to be smart about it.

6) I've seen the same thing happen over and over again with shitcoiners. You'll believe in the project, the team, the goals; yet even the most genius of teams will have their coin see -90% drawdowns in the bear market (best case); no project is immune to market cycles.

5) The example above is best case scenario.

Most commonly you'll ape into space donkey NFTs only to watch your net worth evaporate over a year until the dev dies of 'unnatural causes', making you look like an ass to your wife with nothing to show in the bank.

4) Best case is that the NFT space keeps up, @yugalabs keeps innovating and you're smart enough not to lose your private keys to social engineering scams and hacks, yet you still will never sell because well, he's your ape and this is your community, a true bagholder.

It's easy to get chopped trading on leverage when using weekly candles bc we typically test the bottom of the correction more than once leaving ppl stopped and sidelined before the actual move, so for me spot works a lot better/averaging in slowly if i see what I wanna see

Lines/SR/Ranges help map out where I want to take heavier bets depending on a host of different variables, the higher the timeframe the more they matter to me, but also the longer it can take for price to leave that level in the direction you're trading

and at the end of the day lines are lines they aren't fool proof or religion. The market can simply ignore them/blast through on certain conditions, I don't ever take them as certainties cuz that's how you get fucked

Waiting for extremes requires patience but also doesn't mean intra day trades can't take place or that nothing can be done until the market scams its way into one of them, there's plenty of opportunity outside of btc

8) To me, TA is useful, but it's only part of the equation. There's a lot to learn. What's most important is that it's a tool, and the effectiveness of this tool depends on how well you sharpen and practice with it.

9) Learn to dig. Learn to research, learn to read a

the complete chart history of the coin you're looking to chart. Use https://t.co/hSVaKOFcV2 for example, they tend to track the entire history quite well. The issue with charting on exchanges is that they only use the data starting from the day they list, not the past.

6) There's alpha to be had on twitter, but it'll take some time to discover what that looks like for you. Don't lose it all betting on one call because an anon on twitter told you it was the next 100X play.

7) If you think TA is useful like I do, do yourself a favor and find

trading, start small. Experiment, try leverage out, learn how it works and how it could help/fuck you.

5) There's no 1 right way to do things, despite what the talking heads on twitter say. You're gonna have to fuck up massively and take risks to understand what you're good at.

3) When minting NFT's, always do so from a fresh wallet and only use the funds necessary for the mint, in case you accidentally go on the wrong website (2), at least then you'll be able to minimize the loss. 

4) There's no real right way about it, but if you're going to start

1) Never give out your seed phrase to anyone, especially if his name is Vitalik and promises to send you twice as much back.

2) If you're going to mint an NFT, make sure you're on the correct website, or else you could lose all your $ if you interact with a malicious contract.

This place is the wild west. People here believe that code is law. There's no morals, people will try and exploit any advantage. 

The sooner you realize this, the better.

Crypto is great, but it's also vicious. There's not much more I can say other than try your best to mitigate your risk, be cautious with how you store your keys, always be superstitious when things are too good to be true, and don't click on random links or files.

That's why risk management is really important, from the size of your bets to how you position your portfolio across wallets, exchange accounts and computers. 

It sucks to see people lose it all because they dedicated all their eggs in one basket.

To me, there's no better place to make money than crypto. The flip side is there's rarely any insurance when things go wrong.

Even when cautious, things can go south pretty fast. Even the most experienced people can get into a bad situation. That's something you have to accept.

Taking trading on as a main discipline in concept seems incredible and extremely desirable.

You make your own hours, you're accountable only for yourself, etc etc.

The drawback is that you have nothing to fall back on if you fail, and the odds are stacked against you.
You're probably going to get rinsed at some point. If that doesn't stop you then you're onto something.

And it doesn't always have to be a mechanical rule such as: 

>When price hits resistance, I must sell X amount.

It can be a personal rule as well like:

>If I enter a trade and feel like I have to be lucky for it to play out, I cut the size on that immediately.

This game revolves around making high quality decisions.

You're more likely to make 5 consecutive high quality decisions than 500.

If you're a new trader, I think it quite literally pays to have hard set rules.

You don't have to follow them for the rest of your career but start off with rules that help minimize the amount of decisions you need to make.

On the topic of losses:

If you're a trader that gets rekt by the market after an insane winning streak, it's because winning streaks tend to lead to complacency.. and complacency leads to shitty (sloppy) trading.

It's why it's important to not be too complacent w/ your trading.

I know it's a bull market so we're all winning more than we're losing but just remember that it's extremely important to know how to handle losses.

Have built in circuit breakers. Could be as simple as:

>Taking a break
>Cutting size
>Fixed % drawdowns

Losses beget losses.

I do not know what your optimal timeframe is.

That literally depends on you as a person and your lifestyle.

I've seen people make millions scalping. I've seen people make millions swinging. I've seen people make millions investing.

Same destination, different paths.

Now that you've actually established (realistic) expectations, build a strategy around that.

If you're praying for the 15-min expansion candle that takes you up 50-100%, it COULD happen but be prepared to be disappointed often since you're betting on low probability outcomes.

From the comments, I just feel like people don't necessarily understand.

There is no "perfect" timeframe.

What are your expectations?

Do you want quick 1-3% moves, just in-and-out? Do you want to slowly build a position and swing it over the next few weeks?

You're trading on the 15min chart, maybe even the hourly expecting home runs moves

Without realizing that big moves take days/weeks to play out with many retraces along the way

Strategies not agreeing w/ your expectations is why a lot of you are constantly getting disappointed.
